  "why": "The paper goes beyond merely reporting failures: it systematically characterizes failure cases using uncertainty-based internal measures (PCS, VRO and other Bayesian uncertainty metrics), categorizes inputs into four uncertainty-pattern types (LH, HH, LL, HL), and links these patterns to how failures are produced (e.g., gradient-based adversarial attacks vs. mutation-based testing) and to why some defenses fail (defenses that rely on PCS/VRO are bypassed by uncommon samples). This constitutes partial diagnostic insight based on model-internal uncertainty behavior and statistical failure patterns. However, the paper does not trace failures to deeper root causes such as corrupted or biased training data, reliance on specific spurious features, or explicit neuron- or feature-level causal analysis that would explain underlying vulnerabilities, so it does not meet the criteria for a High rating.",
  "evidence": "Page 2, Abstract: \"We first investigate the capability of multiple uncertainty metrics in differentiating benign examples (BEs) and AEs, which enables to characterize the uncertainty patterns of input data. Then, we identify and categorize the uncertainty patterns of BEs and AEs...\"\n\nPage 6, Section 3.2 (Answer to RQ1): \"Answer to RQ1: PCS of the original model is often effective in distinguishing BEs and AEs generated by existing attacks. For the Bayesian uncertainty metrics, VRO is often more effective than others when comparing the prediction stability between the original model and multiple dropout-enabled predictions.\"\n\nPage 7, Section 3.4 (Answer to RQ2): \"Answer to RQ2: BEs and AEs usually belong to the HL type and LH type, respectively. Compared with state-of-the-art adversarial attacks, testing tools to some extent generate different AEs.\"\n\nPage 7, Section 3.4 (discussion of generation mechanisms): \"Current adversarial attacks usually adopt the gradient-based or optimization-based technique to gradually decrease the predictive probability or the logit value of the truth label... DeepHunter and TensorFuzz adopt the mutation-based technique to generate new tests. The random mutation can not guarantee that the predictive probability of the truth label is decreased gradually...\"\n\nPage 11, Section 5.2 (defense evaluation explanation): \"The reason is that these two techniques mainly depend on the PCS and VRO characteristics for detection. Specifically, binary classifier is trained with the value of logit layer that is closely related to prediction confidence and the label change ratio in mutation-based detection is similar to VRO. The uncommon data is very different from the common data w.r.t. these two metrics. As a result, if they perform well on common data, the success rate on the uncommon data could be low.\""
